=Flight Timetable|website=tui.co.uk|language=en-GB}}</ref><br/>'''Seasonal charter:''' [[Dublin Airport|Dublin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuiholidays.ie/flight/timetable|title=Flight Timetable|publisher=tuiholidays.ie}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[TUI fly Belgium]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Brussels Airport|Brussels]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[TUI fly Deutschland]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport|D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Frankfurt Airport|Frankfurt]], [[Hannover Airport|Hanover]], [[Stuttgart Airport|Stuttgart]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Volotea]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Bordeaux\u2013M\u00e9rignac Airport|Bordeaux]], [[Lyon\u2013Saint-Exup\u00e9ry Airport|Lyon]] (begins 16 April 2020),<ref name=\"VoloteaS20\">{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Volotea S20 new routes as of 29NOV19 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287883/volotea-s20-new-routes-as-of-29nov19/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]] (begins 31 May 2020),<ref name=\"VoloteaS20\"/> [[Marseille Airport|Marseille]], [[Nantes Atlantique Airport|Nantes]], [[Verona Villafranca Airport|Verona]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Vueling]] |'''Seasonal:''' [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport|Barcelona]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Wizz Air]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Vienna International Airport|Vienna]] (begins 4 July 2020)\n<!-- -->\n}}\n\n==Ground transport==\n===Car===\nThe airport is close to the [[List of highways in Portugal|A22]] highway, with connections throughout the [[Algarve]] and direct to [[Lisbon]] and [[Spain]]. Faro airport has 3 different car parking areas. The closest parking area is called \"Parking P0 / P1 \u2013 Classic\", used for short-term visitors, while parking areas P2 and P3 are used for longer term car storage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cheap-taxis.com/faro-airport-transfers/|title=Faro airport transfers - Faro taxis - best taxi rates online|website=Cheap-Taxis.com|access-date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nKiss and Fly is the name for a form of fast parking at the airport. One can drive to the airport to pick up or drop someone off free of charge for up to ten minutes. To drop off passengers, one can stop at the departures curbside and to pick up passengers, you enter the P2 Car Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aeroportofaro.pt/en/fao/access-parking/getting-to-and-from-the-airport/kiss-fly|title=Kiss & Fly - Faro Airport|first=ANA - Aeroportos de|last=Portugal|date=8 July 2016|website=AeroportoFaro.pt|access-date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\nAirport bus routes 14 and 16 run each day between Faro Airport and Faro city centre bus station. From the bus station there are connections to most other Portuguese cities as well as to many Spanish destinations. The airport bus route is currently run by a company called \"Proximo\".\n\n===Railway===\nThe nearest railway station is [[Faro station]] which is about {{Convert|5.7|km}} away and is located close to Faro city centre bus station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.pt/maps/dir/faro+airport/Faro+Train+Station,+Largo+da+Estacao,+Faro/@37.0280767,-7.9642953,15z/data=!3m2!4b1!5s0xd0552b857ad1fd1:0xb825fcec3269135c!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0xd0552b04da7999b:0x2144551e63673b47!2m2!1d-7.96972!2d37.0175956!1m5!1m1!1s0xd0552b856d52a87:0x5060a11e2ca202a3!2m2!1d-7.9397524!2d37.0185499|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps}}</ref> A study into a [[airport rail link|rail link]] to the airport was undertaken in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/studies-to-be-carried-out-on-rail-link-to-faro-airport/45275|title=Studies to be carried out on rail link to Faro Airport|website=The Portugal News|date=11 April 2018|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Taxis===\nPublic taxis are available from the airport and operate 24/7. There are several taxi ranks which you can use to hire a taxi from, or you can use a free phone inside the airport to call a taxi. The majority of curbsidetaxis at the airport will only carry up to four passengers; if you require a bigger taxi, it is best to use to the phone inside.\n\n===Car rentals===\nThere are all major car rental companies that can provide car hire service from the Airport. These companies are mainly located at \"Parking P4 - Car Hire\". Car hire can also be arranged from within the airport.\n\n==Accolades==\nIn 2012, [[Airports Council International]] gave Faro Airport the title of ''Best Improvement'' in Europe.<ref>[[List of Airport Service Quality Award winners#5-15 million]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On 21 December 1992, [[Martinair Flight 495]] sustained a hard landing in bad weather at Faro Airport, killing 54 passengers and two crew out of a total of 340 people on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vliegrampfaro.nl/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Faro_MP495_accident-report-English.pdf|title=Final Report on the Accident Occurring at Faro Airport - Portugal on 21 December 1992}}</ref>\n* On 24 October 2011, an overnight storm collapsed portions of terminal roofs and blew out most windows in the control tower. Four people were slightly injured, one severely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portugaldailyview.com/01-whats-new/portugal-storm-damages-faro-airport-snarls-flights |title=Storm damages Faro airport, snarls flights |date=24 October 2011 |publisher=portugaldailyview.com |access-date=24 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in Portugal]]\n* [[List of airports in Portugal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Faro Airport}}\n* [http://www.ana.pt/en-US/Aeroportos/algarve/Faro/Pages/HomeFaro.aspx Official website]\n* {{ASN|FAO}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Portugal|Aviation}}\n{{Airports in Portugal}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Portugal|Faro Airport]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Faro, Portugal|Airport]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Algarve]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the airport in Yukon, Canada|Faro Airport (Yukon)}}\n{{Distinguish|Paro Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|International airport serving Faro, Portugal}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| nativename = <small>''Aeroporto Internacional de Faro''</small>\n| image2-width = 250\n| location = <!--If different than above-->\n|focus_city    =\n| elevation-m = 7\n| elevation-f = 24\n| metric-elev = Y\n| coordinates = {{coord|37|00|52|N|007|57|57|W|region:PT|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label = LPFR\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| metric-rwy = Y\n| name = Faro Airport\n| image = <!--airport logo-->\n| image-width = 200\n| image2 = FAO FARO AIRPORT PORTUGAL FROM FLIGHT CDG-RAK EASYJET G-EFZI A319 (14778925195).jpg\n| IATA = FAO\n| ICAO = LPFR\n| type = Public\n| owner = ANA Aeroportos de Portugal, S.A.\n| operator = {{nowrap|[[ANA Aeroportos de Portugal]]}}\n| city-served = [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]], [[Algarve]], [[Portugal]]\n| pushpin_map = Portugal\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Portugal\n| website = [http://www.ana.pt/en-US/Aeroportos/algarve/Faro/Pages/HomeFaro.aspx ana.pt]\n| r1-number = 10/28\n| r1-length-m = 2,490\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 8,685,571\n| stat2-header = Passengers change 17-18\n| stat2-data = {{decrease}} 0.5%\n| stat3-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat3-data = 57,352\n| stat4-header = Movements change 17-18\n| stat4-data = {{decrease}} 0.2%\n| stat5-header = Cargo (t)\n| stat5-data = 120\n| stat6-header = Cargo change 17-18\n| stat6-data = {{increase}} 2.9%\n| footnotes = Sources: [[National Institute of Civil Aviation of Portugal|ANAC]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.anac.pt/vPT/Generico/PublicacoesINAC/BoletinsEstatisticosTrimestrais/Paginas/BoletinsEstatisticosTrimestrais.aspx | title = Boletins Estat\u00edsticos Trimestrais | language = Portuguese | trans-title = Quarterly Statistical Bulletins | work = ANAC | publisher = Portuguese Civil Aviation Authority}}</ref> ANA,<ref>{{citation | url = https://www.ana.pt/en/system/files/documents/annual_report_2018.pdf| language = English | title = Annual Report 2018 | date = 15 May 2019 | location = Lisbon | publisher = [[ANA Aeroportos de Portugal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.ana.pt/pt-PT/Topo/Institucional/SobreANA/Imprensa/Noticias/Paginas/Maior-crescimento-de-sempre.aspx?fromlist=1 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160215163528/http://www.ana.pt/pt-PT/Topo/Institucional/SobreANA/Imprensa/Noticias/Paginas/Maior-crescimento-de-sempre.aspx?fromlist=1 | archive-date = 15 February 2016 | lang = Portuguese | title = Aeroportos portugueses com o maior crescimento de sempre | trans-title = Portuguese airports with the highest growth ever | date = 7 January 2016 | publisher = [[ANA Aeroportos de Portugal]]}}</ref> WAD<ref>{{cite web | url = https://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=PO93204 | title = FARO | work = World Aero Data | publisher = WorldAeroData.com | access-date = 2 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Faro Airport''' (Portuguese: ''Aeroporto Internacional de Faro'') {{Airport codes|FAO|LPFR}}, also known as [[Algarve]] Airport, is located {{convert|4|km|abbr=on}} to the west<ref name=\"AIP\">AIP [http://www.nav.pt/ais/cd/2012_03_08_AIRAC/html/index.html Part 3 \u2013 AD 2 Aerodromes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415051720/http://www.nav.pt/ais/cd/2012_03_08_AIRAC/html/index.html |date=15 April 2012 }}</ref> of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]] in Portugal. The airport opened in July 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ana.pt/SiteCollectionDocuments/Negocios_Empresas/Sobre_Aeroportos/ALGARVE_PLANO_DIRECTOR.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-07-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729183505/http://www.ana.pt/SiteCollectionDocuments/Negocios_Empresas/Sobre_Aeroportos/ALGARVE_PLANO_DIRECTOR.pdf |archive-date=29 July 2014}}</ref> A total of 6.4 million passengers used Faro airport in 2015. The airport became a hub for the first time in March 2010, when Ryanair decided to base seven of its aircraft there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ryanair.com/ie/news/39th-base-faro-6ac-28-routes-and-1-3m-pax|title=Official Ryanair website - Cheap flights from Ireland - Ryanair}}</ref> It is very busy from March to October, to the extent that it becomes a slot coordinated airport.<ref name=\"Info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.therouteshop.com/faro-airport/#factsTab|title=Faro Airport (FAO) - Unserved Routes in the Route Shop}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:2017-08-20 Arrivals hall at Faro airport.JPG|thumb|Inside the arrivals hall at Faro airport]]\n[[File:Vorplatz Flughafen Faro.jpg|thumb|The forecourt of the arrivals hall]]\n[[File:Aeroporto de Faro1.jpg|thumb|Terminal building]]\n[[File:Faro Airport at sunset 3.jpg|thumb|Terminal building]]\nFaro Airport is capable of handling six million passengers a year. There are 22 stands of which 16 are remote, with 60 check-in desks and 36 boarding gates.<ref name=\"Info\"/>\n\nSince its opening in 1966 Faro airport has had two major developments: the new passenger terminal building in 1989, and its enlargement in 2001. Faced with growing traffic demand and passenger safety and satisfaction needs, the development plan for 2009\u20132013 saw Faro airport undergo extensive improvements to runway and infrastructure, as well as a widespread renovation of the airport terminal and commercial areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.airport-technology.com/projects/faro-international-airport-terminal-expansion/|title=Faro International Airport Terminal Expansion|website=Airport Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the airports in Lisbon, Porto, Ponta Delgada, Santa Maria, Horta, Flores, Madeira, and Porto Santo, the airport's concessions to provide support to civil aviation were conceded to [[ANA Aeroportos de Portugal]] on 18 December 1998, under provisions of decree 404/98. With this concession, ANA became responsible for the planning, development and construction of future infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.porto-airport-car-rental.com/the-history-of-porto-airport-francisco-de-sa-carneiro-airport/|title=The history of Porto Airport - Francisco de S\u00e1 Carneiro Airport|date=1 February 2017|website=Porto-Airport-Car-Rental.com|access-date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\nThe following airlines operate regular scheduled direct passenger flights at Faro Airport:\n\n{{Airport destination list\n<!-- -->\n| [[Aer Lingus]] | [[Dublin Airport|Dublin]]<br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Cork Airport|Cork]], [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air France]] | [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]] (begins 4 April 2020)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Air France S20 Spain/Portugal network additions |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287074/air-france-s20-spainportugal-network-additions/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Air Transat]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Toronto Pearson International Airport|Toronto\u2013Pearson]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[British Airways]] | [[Gatwick Airport|London\u2013Gatwick]]<br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[London City Airport|London\u2013City]], [[Heathrow Airport|London\u2013Heathrow]], [[London Stansted Airport|London\u2013Stansted]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Brussels Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Brussels Airport|Brussels]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Chair Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Z\u00fcrich Airport|Z\u00fcrich]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Corendon Airlines]] | [[Brussels Airport|Brussels]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Corendon Dutch Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]], [[Maastricht-Aachen Airport|Maastricht/Aachen]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[easyJet]] | [[Belfast International Airport|Belfast\u2013International]], [[Berlin Sch\u00f6nefeld Airport|Berlin\u2013Sch\u00f6nefeld]], [[Bordeaux\u2013M\u00e9rignac Airport|Bordeaux]], [[Bristol Airport|Bristol]], [[Glasgow Airport|Glasgow]], [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport|Liverpool]], [[Gatwick Airport|London\u2013Gatwick]], [[Luton Airport|London\u2013Luton]], [[London Southend Airport|London\u2013Southend]], [[Lyon\u2013Saint-Exup\u00e9ry Airport|Lyon]], [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], [[Milan\u2013Malpensa Airport|Milan\u2013Malpensa]], [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Nice C\u00f4te d'Azur Airport|Nice]], [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]], [[Orly Airport|Paris\u2013Orly]], [[Toulouse\u2013Blagnac Airport|Toulouse]] <br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Berlin Tegel Airport|Berlin\u2013Tegel]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[easyJet Switzerland]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[EuroAirport Basel\u2013Mulhouse\u2013Freiburg|Basel/Mulhouse]], [[Geneva International Airport|Geneva]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Edelweiss Air]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Z\u00fcrich Airport|Z\u00fcrich]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Eurowings]]| [[Cologne Bonn Airport|Cologne/Bonn]], [[Munich Airport|Munich]], [[Stuttgart Airport|Stuttgart]]<br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Hamburg Airport|Hamburg]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Iberia Regional]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Jet2.com]] | [[Birmingham Airport|Birmingham]], [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]], [[Leeds Bradford Airport|Leeds/Bradford]], [[London Stansted Airport|London\u2013Stansted]], [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]] <br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Belfast International Airport|Belfast\u2013International]], [[Edinburgh Airport|Edinburgh]], [[Glasgow Airport|Glasgow]], [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Jet Time]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Helsinki Airport|Helsinki]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Lauda (airline)|Lauda]] | [[Vienna International Airport|Vienna]] <br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \n<!-- -->\n| [[Lufthansa]] | [[Frankfurt Airport|Frankfurt]], [[Munich Airport|Munich]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Luxair]] | [[Luxembourg Findel Airport|Luxembourg]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Norwegian Air Shuttle]] | [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport|Stockholm\u2013Arlanda]]<br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Billund Airport|Billund]], [[Copenhagen Airport|Copenhagen]], [[Oslo Airport, Gardermoen|Oslo\u2013Gardermoen]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Ryanair]]| [[Beauvais\u2013Till\u00e9 Airport|Beauvais]], [[Orio al Serio International Airport|Bergamo]], [[Berlin Tegel Airport|Berlin\u2013Tegel]], [[Birmingham Airport|Birmingham]], [[Bournemouth Airport|Bournemouth]], [[Brussels South Charleroi Airport|Charleroi]], [[Dublin Airport|Dublin]], [[East Midlands Airport|East Midlands]], [[Edinburgh Airport|Edinburgh]], [[Eindhoven Airport|Eindhoven]], [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport|Glasgow\u2013Prestwick]], [[London Stansted Airport|London\u2013Stansted]], [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]], [[Marseille Airport|Marseille]], [[Memmingen Airport|Memmingen]], [[Francisco de S\u00e1 Carneiro Airport|Porto]] <br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Aberdeen Airport|Aberdeen]], [[Bordeaux\u2013M\u00e9rignac Airport|Bordeaux]], [[Bristol Airport|Bristol]], [[Cardiff Airport|Cardiff]], [[Cork Airport|Cork]], [[Frankfurt Airport|Frankfurt]], [[Kerry Airport|Kerry]], [[Ireland West Airport Knock|Knock]], [[Leeds Bradford International Airport|Leeds/Bradford]], [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport|Liverpool]], [[Luton Airport|London\u2013Luton]], [[London Southend Airport|London\u2013Southend]], [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Cornwall Airport Newquay|Newquay]], [[Shannon Airport|Shannon]], [[Warsaw Modlin Airport|Warsaw\u2013Modlin]], [[Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw|Wroc\u0142aw]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Scandinavian Airlines]] | [[Copenhagen Airport|Copenhagen]], [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport|Stockholm\u2013Arlanda]]<br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Oslo Airport, Gardermoen|Oslo\u2013Gardermoen]]<ref name=\"SAS S19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/280960/sas-s19-european-network-additions/|title=SAS S19 European network additions|website=Routesonline}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n| [[Smartwings]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Katowice Airport|Katowice]],<ref name=\"Smartwing